Poenino. This was the pass of the Great St Bernard. Its name is thought to be derived from the Celtic deity Penn (Zeuss‚ die Deutschen‚ p. 5). Jupiter Poem'nus was worshipped on the summit, and the name has been found on''30⁷ ex voto tablets which have been discovered near the top. It was also called Mons Jovis, which survive-s in the names Mont-Joux‚ Plan-de-Joux which are still localized on the height. It was by this pass that Livy, v. 35, brought the Boii and Lingones into Italy in the 5th century ac. The fanciful derivation of the name referred to in the text was an argument likely to be urged in early times.
